'''Fcitx''' (Free Chinese Input Toy for X) is a Chinese input method. You can install Fcitx by using the following command:

{{Emerge|app-i18n/fcitx}}

== Use Flags ==

{{USEflag|package=app-i18n/fcitx
|cairo+yes+
|gtk++yes+Lets you use fcitx in Gtk(2) programs
|pango+yes+
|table+yes++Adds suppport for Wubi, Erbi & etc.
|debug
|gtk3++yes+Lets you use fcitx in Gtk3 programs
|opencc
|qt++yes+Lets you use fcitx in qt programs
|static-libs
|zhengma+++Adds support for Zhengma
}}

It is strongly recommended to add gtk, gtk3 and qt in USE.

== Using Fcitx ==

In order to use Fcitx in X, you need to add these environment variables(You need to <code>export</code> them after setting these variables):

If you use GDM, KDM or LightDM to login, add them to ~/.xprofile. If you use startx, SLiM, etc. to login, add them to ~/.xinitrc.

<pre>
XIM=fcitx
XIM_PROGRAM=fcitx
XMODIFIERS="@im=fcitx"
QT_IM_MODULE=<module>
GTK_IM_MODULE=<module>
</pre>

If you add gtk, gtk3 and qt to <code>USE</code>, &lt;module&gt; will be `fcitx', otherwise it should be `xim'.

<!--
Note: If you want to use Fcitx in English language, you may add <code>LC_CTYPE=zh_CN.UTF-8</code> in environment.
-->

Note: If you want to use Fcitx in X, your [[locale]] '''CANNOT''' be `C' or `POSIX'.

== Configuration ==

You can edit Fcitx's configuration file at <code>~/.config/fcitx/config</code>.

Also, there is a tool to configure Fcitx called {{Package|app-i18n/fcitx-configtool}} (You may need to add the '~arch' keyword in package.accept_keywords to install it).

